records.addlTxt:
Sentencing hearing proceeded. Court finds the State has complied with the victim rights legislation. Statements made as to sentencing. 

As to COUNT 1-
Court ordered defendant to serve 90 DAYS in the House of Correction consecutive to COUNT 3; straight time with the exception that if the defendant is employed at the time of revocation, he may have release for work; 

As to COUNT 3-
Court ordered defendant to serve 180 DAYS in the House of Correction consecutive to COUNT 1; straight time with the exception that if the defendant is employed at the time of revocation, he may have release for work;

Court STAYED the sentence on COUNTS 1 & 3 and placed defendant on probation for 24 MONTHS with the following conditions:

1) Court ordered 60 days of condition time in the House of Correction on COUNT 3, IMPOSED BUT STAYED to be used at the discretion of the agent;
2) Pay all costs, fees and surcharges (including the Domestic Abuse Assessment) during period of probation. Defendant to enter into a payment plan with the Department. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment;
3) Provide DNA sample and pay DNA surcharge. Court WAIVED DNA surcharge on COUNT 3 as it is part of a continuous event;
4) No contact with the victim or her place of residence or employment;
5) Attend a Batterer's Intervention Program;
6) AODA Assessment and comply with recommended treatment;
7) No possession of firearms;

Court advised the defendant of the federal ban on firearms and that he may be subject to federal prosecution for a violation of this ban.

It is the Court's intention the credit for time served in this case be applied to the defendant's other pending case 15CM1063. 

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 
Filed;
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
Memorandum of Conditions of Probation;
Pretrial Incarceration Credit. 
Probation Review Hearing scheduled for October 23, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
